| rev7Score = 7.4/10<ref name="Mitchum"/>
| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''
| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="Moon"/>
| rev9 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''
| rev9Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name="Uncut"/>
}}
''The Headphone Masterpiece'' was well received by contemporary [[music criticism|music critics]]. [[Allmusic]] editor Mike Gowan dubbed it a "lo-fi gem" and " an eclectic celebration of sound."<ref name="Gowan">{{cite web|last=Gowan|first=Mike|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-headphone-masterpiece-mw0000660512|title=The Headphone Masterpiece <U+2013> Cody ChesnuTT|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=October 28, 2012}}</ref> Tom Moon of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' cited it as "one of the most emotionally raw albums of the year" and wrote that it "gathers musical strands from all over the pop universe into unadorned, remarkably intimate stream-of-consciousness musings on love, money and responsibility".<ref name="Moon">{{cite journal|last=Moon|first=Tom|date=October 3, 2002|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090326074929/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/267186/review/6068233/theheadphonemasterpiece|title=The Headphone Masterpiece : Cody ChesnuTT : Review|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|issue=906|accessdate=October 28, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BkBaxkEQ|archivedate=October 28, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' called the album "an awesome declaration of intent" and stated, "Although decidedly lo-fi, this epic, adventurous and mischievous album bears comparison with [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] and [[Todd Rundgren]] (at their respective peaks)."<ref name="Uncut">{{cite journal|month=June|year=2003|page=91|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/node/9566|title=Review: The Headphone Masterpiece|journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|location=London|accessdate=October 28, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BkBnrbsk|archivedate=October 28, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Matt Diehl of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' called it "indie soul that traverses the chasm between [[Shuggie Otis]] and [[Guided by Voices]]".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Diehl|first=Matt|date=July 21, 2003|url=http://admin.spin.com/articles/bands-watch-cody-chesnutt|title=Bands to Watch: Cody Chesnutt|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref> [[Dream Hampton]], writing in ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'', said that the album is "everything that many roots and retro artists have reached for, pure and straightforward; yet it is thoroughly modern in its outlook, inventive and unsentimental, with both feet in the future."<ref name="Hampton"/>

''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' found the album to be "at once engaging and aloof", and wrote that it "entices you closer yet keeps its distance, its often hamfisted production and errant vocals adding to its ramshackle, rusticated charms".<ref name="Mojo">{{cite journal|title=Review: The Headphone Masterpiece|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|location=London|month=September|year=2003|page=106}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' found it "musically uneven in the best way" and called the album "a brilliant, self-indulgent, kaleidoscopic, contradictory mess".<ref name="Rabin">{{cite news|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|authorlink=Nathan Rabin|date=December 18, 2002|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/cody-chesnutt-the-headphone-masterpiece,12185/|title=Cody ChesnuTT: The Headphone Masterpiece|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|location=Chicago|accessdate=October 28, 2012}}</ref> [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Rob Mitchum observed "a surplus of uniqueness overshadows a respectable aptitude" and commented that its "self-indulgence, lack of focus, and unbridled sonic and lyrical crudity" makes the album "so frustrating, yet compelling."<ref name="Mitchum">{{cite web|last=Mitchum|first=Rob|date=January 14, 2003|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/1426-the-headphone-masterpiece/|title=Cody ChesnuTT: The Headphone Masterpiece|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=October 28, 2012}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' gave the album a two-star honorable mention,<ref name="Christgau">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=March 25, 2003|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2003-03-25/music/as-long-as-i-still-can/http/|title=As Long as I Still Can|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|accessdate=October 28, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?id=5088&name=Cody+Chesnutt|archivedate=October 28, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> indicating a "likable effort consumers attuned to its overriding aesthetic or individual vision may well enjoy."<ref>{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|year=2000|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bk-cg90/grades-90s.php|title=Key to Icons|publisher=Robert Christgau|accessdate=October 28, 2012}}</ref> Christgau cited "Family on Blast", "The World Is Coming to My Party", and "My Woman, My Guitars" as highlights and quipped, "just what [[neo soul|alt-r&b]] needed<U+2014>loads of ideas, considerable talent, and all the stern self-discipline of a trust fund baby".<ref name="Christgau"/>

